The riding position is more aggressive, with handlebars wider spaced and slightly farther forward, and footrests 10mm farther back. Despite this the SP has a familiar Fireblade feel. It seems almost old-fashioned to start such a fancy new superbike simply by turning the ignition key, pressing the starter button, selecting first gear and letting out the clutch, with no thought to settings or modes.
One of the Fireblade’s strengths in recent years has been its flexible, rider-friendly nature – by the standards of 170bhp-plus rocket-ships, that is. Throttle response is flawless. Once into its stride at 6,000rpm the motor builds power in a wonderfully strong, consistent surge to the redline at 13,000rpm.
The Honda lacks the frenzied top-end charge of its most powerful rivals but with a top speed of more than 170mph it’s an incredibly fast motorcycle. On the main straight at the flowing, if featureless, Losail circuit in Qatar it was still accelerating at more than 160mph, despite a strong headwind that was whistling over the subtly reshaped, more aerodynamic screen.
The main benefit of weight-matched pistons is reduced vibration. The SP is certainly smooth, even at high revs, though you’d have to be very familiar with the current model to notice a difference. Its gearchange is good, although the lack of an electronic quick-shifter is disappointing.
Honda’s aluminium twin-spar frame is revised around the swing-arm pivot area, to provide slightly more flex for improved feedback. The firm’s chassis development work with Swedish suspension expert Öhlins, which provides the front forks and rear shock, also resulted in new triple clamps for extra rigidity at the steering head.
The handling is predictably excellent, the suspension giving a subtly more taut, racer-like feel, with minimal pitching under acceleration and braking. High-speed stability is impeccable, the steering very neutral and precise.
Braking is outstandingly powerful and controllable, boosted by the adoption of Brembo’s Monobloc calipers. The combined ABS system is revised based on feedback from the Honda Legends endurance racing team, with the front and rear systems being linked to a slightly reduced degree.
This bike is not built for comfort, let alone pillions. Its single seat is firmer, for more precise feedback. A cut-down rear subframe saves some weight. The SP is unashamedly the most purposeful, least practical Fireblade yet, and the best suited to hard riding.
What makes the SP stand out even more is the way this most exotic of Fireblades eschews the modern trend towards electronic rider aids. Would it be more versatile and safer if it featured multiple riding modes, traction control and electronically adjustable or semiactive suspension? Probably, although inevitably it would also cost more than the already steep price of £14,999.
There’s no doubt that a sizeable band of hardcore super-sports riders, including many existing Fireblade owners, will be delighted with it just the way it is. Honda’s traditional approach has retained the model’s trademark poise, while creating what, for track use at least, is undoubtedly the sharpest and best ’Blade yet. THE FACTS
Honda CBR1000RR Fireblade SP Tested: 999cc four-stroke four, six-speed transmission Price/on sale: £14,999 (£15,599 with ABS)/February Power/torque: 178bhp @ 12,250rpm/84lb ft @ 10,500rpm Top speed: 180mph (estimated) Range: 120 miles @ 38mpg (estimated) Verdict: Exotic, track-focused version of Honda's super-sports four. Fast, refined, sweet-handling and well equipped, but expensive and lacking some of its rivals' high-tech features Telegraph rating: Four out of five stars RIVALS
BMW HP4, £16,700 This even more advanced version of the awesome S1000RR holds its 190bhp four-cylinder engine in a high-tech chassis incorporating semi-active suspension. Ducati 1199 Panigale, £15,995 Even the "basic" version of Ducati's 1198cc V-twin combines 195bhp performance with multiple riding modes, ABS, quick-shifter and drop-dead gorgeous looks. MV Agusta F4R, £14,499 This mid-ranking model of the Italian marque's 998cc fours produces 192bhp and has an Öhlins shock. Stylish, fast and raw but lacks the Honda's refinement. Honda
