BBC's Diamond Jubilee coverage 'cringingly inept', says Michael Buerk
Michael Buerk has attacked the BBC’s coverage of the Queen’s Diamond Jubilee celebrations as “cringingly inept”, singling out Strictly Come Dancing's Tess Daly for being a "bird-brain” presenter. Michael Buerk has attacked the BBC’s coverage of the Queen’s Diamond Jubilee celebrations Photo: Geoff Pugh	By Stephen Adams
11:43AM GMT 30 Dec 2012
In a sweeping broadside against coverage of the Thames Pageant in particular, the veteran BBC journalist said he was “so ashamed” that he almost wept. In an article reviewing the year for The Mail on Sunday, he accused the presenters of being ignorant of the monarchy and British history, and instead focusing on speaking to “even more vacuous D-list celebrities”. He reserved special loathing for Daly's contribution, describing her as “a pneumatic bird-brain from Strictly Come Dancing”. Referring to the way June's Thames river pageant was covered by the BBC, Buerk said: "The one enduring British institution was mocked by another that had shamefully lost its way."
"Out on the water, a tribute to the Monarch that resonated back to the Middle Ages, rich in historical continuities, a floating salute to past glory and present fortitude. On the screen, a succession of Daytime airheads preened themselves, or gossiped with even more vacuous D-list 'celebrities'. With barely an exception, they were cringingly inept. Related Articles
Climbed Every Mountain, BBC Two
29 Dec 2012
Armstrong’s family: origins of 'one small step'
30 Dec 2012
Ripper Street
30 Dec 2012
"Nobody knew anything and nobody cared. The main presenter couldn't even work out what to call the Queen,” he noted, referring to the fact that she was mistakenly referred to as Her Royal Highness, rather than Her Majesty. He continued: "The Dunkirk Little Ships, the most evocative reminders of this country's bravest hour, were ignored so that a pneumatic bird-brain from Strictly Come Dancing could talk to transvestites in Battersea Park. "I was so ashamed of the BBC I would have wept if I hadn't been so angry. The worst thing was that it was deliberate - planned than way to be ‘light’ and ‘inclusive’.”
The corporation received more than 2,400 complaints from the public about some of its live broadcasts over the weekend, with much of the blame being directed at George Entwistle, the then head of BBC Vision who went on to become director-general. The BBC was so out of touch that he said it "actually congratulated itself" for the Jubilee coverage "and the executive ultimately responsible [Entwistle] was promptly promoted to become the most disastrous director-general in the corporation's history". UK News
