Wasps see off Gloucester and set their sights on a top-four finish in the Premiership
Wasps’ bid to return to Europe’s elite continues to gather momentum. Fuelled by another storming performance from Billy Vunipola, Gloucester became their latest victims as the London club won 33-29 and kept their sights fixed on a top-four finish.
In the acsendant: Billy Vunipola led the charge for Wasps Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Gary Fitzgerald
11:37PM GMT 17 Feb 2013
Comments
Vunipola, the England No 8 prospect, charged over for a second-half try while another Saxons starlet, wing Christian Wade, made it 12 tries for the season. Gloucester caused a few flutters of anxiety in the closing stages but Wasps were not to be denied. Victory keeps Dai Young’s resurgent side nicely placed in fourth, well set for the Premiership play-offs, although they will need to reinforce their defence if they are to maintain their upward trajectory. They were leading 33-17 with eight minutes left here, but opened up with alarming regularity in the closing stages so that Gloucester were able to secure two precious bonus points. Still, the club who were in such disarray on and off the field last year continue to threaten to bring back their European glory days. Young said: “We have not played well for 80 minutes all season but we’re still growing as a team and learning. We still have a lot to improve on and we are heading in the right direction. We are not hammering teams and we are having a little rub of the green. But we just have to keep on playing and getting the wins and the points. “It was an entertaining game for the neutral but we need to come out of the blocks quicker and make sure we’re not continuously playing catch up. We put ourselves out of sight but then Gloucester came back strongly near the end. We coughed the ball up and gave them a couple of opportunities and all of a sudden everyone is on their toes.”
