Scrum-half Dan Robson helped Gloucester to make the perfect start. After full-back Rob Cook had kicked the visitors ahead, flanker Akapusi Qera broke through the Wasps defence before feeding Robson, who ran over unchallenged. A Stephen Jones penalty calmed the nerves of the Adams Park crowd, who were then on their feet to applaud flanker Ashley Johnson as he deployed his power and strength to go over for Wasps’ opening try. Gloucester played with flair, freedom and a desire to attack, but they were confronted by a set of Wasps forwards who were determined to let nothing past, and after Cook and Jones exchanged penalties, the hosts went in at half-time 13-10 ahead. Gloucester enjoyed some reward for their adventure in the second period, and they edged ahead when fly-half Ryan Mills fed Mike Tindall, who rediscovered some of his old pace to break through Chris Bell’s less than impressive tackle to run across the line. But Wasps’ resilience was never in doubt. Jones reduced Gloucester’s lead to a point before they were blown away in a devastating spell of rugby, which was sparked by the irrepressible Wade. Vunipola picked up a loose ball on halfway to feed the wing and, despite the pass arriving high, Wade collected smartly and dashed 50 metres for the line, evading Jonny May’s tackle in the process. Jones converted to give Wasps a 23-17 lead before Vunipola ­delivered his party piece in the 69th minute. The Australian-born 20-year-old smashed past two tackles from a scrum 15 metres out for the decisive try, with replacement Nick Robinson adding both the conversion and a subsequent ­penalty. “If you give Christian a bit of space there are very few better,” Young said. “People underestimate his strength and power and he has great footwork. If he keeps performing like that he will no doubt get his opportunity for honours. His try was crucial as it gave us the momentum and confidence to go on and win the match.” Gloucester director of rugby Nigel Davies refused to be too dejected at the end, preferring to focus on his side’s enterprise and late resilience, which yielded tries for Mills and Charlie Sharples. He said: “You like to think that when you score four tries away from home you will win the game 99 per cent of the time. Unfortunately, this was the one per cent. “We allowed them to take control of the game but we have managed to come away with two bonus points, having scored four tries. It is crucial to keep the points ticking over and this keeps us in the hunt for a top-four spot.”
