Google Maps and Twitter mashup show UK snowfall
A Google Maps mashup that allows Twitter users to plot areas of UK snowfall is taking the internet by storm
Ben Marsh's website has used Google Maps with Twitter in order to provide updates about the heavy UK snow falls By Claudine Beaumont
12:03PM GMT 02 Feb 2009
Comments
The map, created by software programmer Ben Marsh, combines Google Maps with tagged Twitter messages. All Twitter users have to do is send a Tweet containing the first part of their postcode, and giving the snowfall a mark out of 10. It is then automatically displayed on Ben Marsh's Google Map, providing a real-time record of snowfall across the country. The site automatically updates every minute, and has received hundreds of tweets so far. London and the south-east is well represented on the map, with other parts of the country slowly joining in as the band of snow moves northwards. Twitter users should send their tweet in the following format: #uksnow [THEIR POSTCODE] [SCORE out of]/10.
The #uksnow hash-tag first appeared on Twitter late yesterday afternoon, and seems to have been created by Twitter user Julian Bray, who used the hash-tag in reponse to a tweet from TV presenter Philip Schofield , who was worried the blizzard might prevent him getting home. The hash-tag is also being used on the Flickr photo-sharing website, while Twitter's search engine facility is ranking the topic among its hottest trends , alongside such subjects as the Super Bowl and Fern Britton, who is having to present This Morning on her own today with a skeleton staff, much to the amusement of Twitter users working from home. Related Articles
